## The Proposed Architecture

### Layer 1 — Physical Foundation Data Collection
Collect raw multi-axis inertial data at scale across physical 
domains:

- Flight (fixed wing, rotary, FPV, commercial aviation)
- Ground vehicles (automotive, motorsport, off-road)
- Marine (hull dynamics, wave response)
- Human movement (sport, daily activity, impact, fall)
- Industrial machinery (vibration, load cycles, wear signatures)
- Manipulation (robotic and human — grasping, force, compliance)
- Natural phenomena (wind, water, seismic)

High-frequency IMU logging (1kHz+), multi-sensor fusion, 
event-labelled, outcome-tagged. Reality as it actually is, 
not as equations predict it should be.

### Layer 2 — Foundation Model Training
Train on this physical dataset as a primary modality — the same 
way language models are trained on text corpora. Not fine-tuning. 
Not a module. Foundation-level training that builds physical 
intuition into the base weights.

The model learns:
- What momentum feels like at different scales
- What surface contact signatures look like in inertial data
- What failure, stress, and anomaly feel like vs normal operation
- How physical systems behave across the full variance of 
  real-world conditions — not idealised simulations

### Layer 3 — Inheritance
Every AI system, robotics platform, autonomous vehicle, or 
embodied agent built on this foundation inherits physical 
intuition without additional collection or training.

A surgical robot gets physical understanding.  
A humanoid gets physical understanding.  
An autonomous vehicle gets physical understanding.  
All from the same foundational layer, collected once.

